http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Debate III is a two-semester course designed to lead students to a mastery of advanced oral communication and argumentation skills. Students in Debate III will express ideas and present information in a variety of formal presentations and debate formats. Students will construct argumentative positions using scientific and technical research on complex, controversial issues. Content will focus on the centrality of oral advocacy to the legal system and the democratic process. Peer adjudication will be an important part of the Debate III process.
Research
Students will master advanced research skills necessary for effective argumentation and debate.

Organize a debate:
  • budgetary needs
  • community resources
  • networks within the community
  • parameters of the format

Synthesize information from research using scientific and technical texts:
  • central ideas
  • explanation for actions and events
  • government database
  • primary and secondary sources
  • private database
  • professional journals
  • social networking
  • specialized vocabulary
  • subscription database
  • summaries
  • textual evidence

Construct argumentative positions:
  • affirmative case formats
  • off case arguments (e.g., counterplans, counter warrants, debate theory, disadvantages, kritiks, solvency turns, topicality attacks)

Analyze exhaustive topic-specific research:
  • major topic areas
  • multiple alternative positions for each subtopic area
  • relative strength of sources
  • relevant and irrelevant facts
Legal Debate
Students will participate in legal debate.

Discuss the centrality of oral advocacy to the democratic process:
  • citizen involvement
  • implements impact of oral arguments
  • personal freedoms
Convene sessions using National Mock Trial Rules
Employ the Federal Rules of Evidence Mock Trial Version

Compose written case arguments:
  • closing
  • crossing
  • directs
  • openings

Analyze case materials as provided by the currently released case for the Arkansas Mock Trial program, currently released National High School Mock Trial case, or by the case database of the National High School Mock Trial Association
Use peer pair collaboration to produce convincing witness testimony
Collaborate in teams to produce convincing theories of the case
Presentation
Students will master the presentation and delivery of complex arguments during debate.
Advocate employing the reasoning in seminal United States texts and legal documents
Model exemplary extemporaneous delivery
Recognize the visual impact of personal delivery
Employ creativity and originality in speaking arguments
Manage time effectively
Conduct debriefing sessions
Employ pathos in language choices
